<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / UB shows transatlantic scars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
United Biscuits, the UK biscuits and snack manufacturer, showed the scars of
competition on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday with sweeping
restructuring charges totalling Pounds 121m. Its US subsidiary Keebler will
undergo radical changes in distribution and manufacture. In Europe there
will be 500 job losses, with three quarters of that in the UK.
The charges helped pull UB's pre-tax profit down to Pounds 116.7m for the
year, a fall of 28 per cent. Underlying profit was also lower at UB's
all-important UK biscuit and snacks businesses. Mr Eric Nicoli, chief
executive, said this was due less to competition than to rises in raw
material prices, partly caused by sterling's devaluation, which the group
was unable to pass on at a time of low inflation.
In the US, restructuring costs will total Pounds 92.5m, of which Pounds
11.2m had already been announced for the closure of a snack factory at
Raleigh, North Carolina. Keebler, which has only 4 per cent of the US salted
snack market, is to withdraw from 25 per cent of the US geographically. UB
said it lost money on Dollars 250m (Pounds 171m) of snack sales last year,
and had made no profit in snacks since attacking the market five years ago.
In US biscuits, UB said, most of the cost would be incurred in switching
from an advance ordering system towards van selling. Some biscuit
manufacturing lines would be closed, but no factories. Production was not
expected to fall below last year's reduced level, and UB would not withdraw
from any part of the US biscuit market.
Mr John Warren, finance director, said job losses in Europe would come
across all divisions, both in headquarters and at factories. Most of the
jobs would be in middle management, he said, with losses in the UK
proportionate to the numbers employed there.
Mr Nicoli said recovery at Keebler, which had a management upheaval last
year, was already under way. Profits in dollar terms were up 39 per cent
before exceptionals, and by 55 per cent in the second half. 'The difference
in calibre between the new management team and the old one is very marked,'
he said. 'They have a very detailed plan for the next two or three years.
The initiatives which underly the provisions are by no means the whole
story.'
Rebutting suggestions that Keebler's troubles made UB too dependent on the
UK market, Mr Nicoli said Europe and the Asia Pacific region contributed 20
per cent of last year's sales and 22 per cent of profits. 'For the fourth
year running we've reported improved sales, profits and margins in
continental Europe,' he said. 'Not many people can say that.'
Mr Warren said restructuring would involve cash outlays of Pounds 45m this
year and Pounds 20m in each of the following two years. All the European
costs would be incurred this year, while the US programme would be spread
over three. The whole programme is claimed to yield savings of more than
Pounds 50m a year by 1997.
The dividend was held unchanged at 15.3p for the year. UB's shares rose 11p
to 349p.
Lex, Page 20; Details, Page 23
</TEXT>
