<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / LVMH surges 19% and sees strong growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LVMH, the French luxury goods group, yesterday announced net profits of
FFr3.57bn (Pounds 400m) for 1993, a 19 per cent increase over the previous
year, and forecast strong earnings growth this year.
Mr Bernard Arnault, chairman, said encouraging developments had emerged
since the final quarter of 1993. He cited economic recovery in the US and
the UK, improved champagne sales, lower financial charges and a
strengthening of the Japanese cognac market. The improvement was reflected
in sales figures for the first two months which, he said, rose by 28 per
cent compared with the same period in 1993.
The group said net profits should rise by more than 20 per cent this year if
the progress experienced in the past few months continued. The share price
climbed by nearly 5 per cent to FFr4,389.
Last year's profits were boosted by exceptional gains, largely resulting
from the sale of the group's RoC cosmetics business. Without these FFr602m
gains, the company would have recorded profits of FFr2.97bn, a slight fall
on 1992 but still at the top end of expectations. Sales grew 10 per cent to
FFr23.8bn.
The performance of the cognac and champagne businesses contrasted with
luggage and perfumes. Operating profits from cognac and spirits fell from
FFr2.29bn to FFr1.91bn due to depressed demand, while champagne produced a
flat contribution of FFr780m despite a 7 per cent rise in turnover. In
luggage and leather goods, operating profits grew from FFr1.87bn to
FFr2.32bn, while perfumes and beauty products advanced from FFr809m to
FFr852m.
Earnings growth this year is expected to be supported by reduced financial
charges resulting from the reorganisation of its shareholdings with Guinness
of the UK. The January reorganisation, in which Guinness swapped its
indirect 24 per cent stake in LVMH for a direct stake in the French group's
champagne activities, brought proceeds of about FFr11bn for LVMH.
Industry observers expect LVMH to take full control of Guerlain, one of
France's most famous fragrance houses in which it has a 15 per cent stake.
A dividend of FFr15 per share, an increase of 10 per cent, is proposed.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
