<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Top insolvency watchdog plans 3-yearly checks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The largest of the UK's newly created bodies for regulating insolvency
practitioners plans to examine all 1,200 professionals under its charge in
the next five years.
It also plans to inspect every active insolvency practitioner - about
three-quarters of the total - every three years, it said yesterday.
The details were revealed by Miss Kay Linnell, who was appointed chief
executive of the Joint Insolvency Monitoring Unit on Monday.
The unit will take responsibility for monitoring the practitioners licensed
by the Insolvency Practitioners Association, the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales, and the members outside Scotland of the
Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland.
The three bodies, which retain control of licensing and disciplining their
members, respectively hold three, four and one seat on the board. They will
pay a contribution to the unit based on their number of practitioners.
Miss Linnell said she planned to hire two support staff and about eight
inspectors, who would examine about 100 practitioners each year.
She said the unit would consider basic compliance with regulations,
subjective areas such as whether litigation should have been commenced, and
wider topics including fees charged. 'Our motto is to be firm but fair,' she
said.
The unit was set up after monitoring by the government insolvency service
found a high proportion of practitioners failing to meet legal obligations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
