<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Accountancy groups retreat from merger plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Growing signs of dissent are emerging among the UK's six principal
accountancy bodies as they prepare a statement proposing a restructuring of
the profession which could lead to a merger.
At least half the bodies are expected to issue letters to their members in
the next few days expressing disapproval of the statement or at the least
failing to endorse its conclusions.
The statement calls for the combination of the six bodies into three
regional institutes of chartered accountants, with all members sharing the
designation 'chartered accountant'.
In an effort to present a single proposal for the future, none is expected
to veto the statement when it is discussed on Monday by the consultative
committee of accountancy bodies, which represents the six groups.
It comes after nearly a year of talks in a working group chaired by Mr David
Bishop, a partner with KPMG Peat Marwick. Each body will consult its members
and report in November.
The Chartered Association of Certified Accountants inflamed the debate last
night when Mr Kenneth Duncan, its president, said at its annual dinner that
an immediate merger would not work and called instead for closer
co-operation under the existing structure.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland is opposed to a merger
and has been angered by the Bishop group's failure to discuss its
alternative proposals in detail.
The Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy is expected to
take a neutral position on the statement. The Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales, the Institute of Chartered Accountants in
Ireland, and the Chartered Institute of Management Accountants are mainly in
favour.
The statement, which contains 12 'principles', calls for common assessment
standards and common entry standards for education and training.
It says the three new bodies would co-operate closely on issues of common
interest, such as international policy and education, through a successor
body to the existing consultative committee.
It recommends that this committee should include lay members for
consideration of issues in the public interest such as practice regulation,
ethics, discipline and professional standards.
</TEXT>
