<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / School start-age suggestion is 'absurd'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, dismissed as 'absurd' a suggestion
that the school starting age should be raised from five to six to finance
universal nursery education.
Mr Patten said: 'I have no intention at all of bringing forward plans for
compulsory schooling for three and four-year-olds.'
The suggestion was made yesterday in a report from the Royal Society of Arts
which also suggested that parents should be required to sign a contract to
stay together until their children reach 16.
The current provision of pre-school education was 'little short of a
national scandal', it said, and called for half-day nursery education for
all three and four-year-olds by 1999.
The report's author, Sir Christopher Ball, a former warden of Keble College,
Oxford, said: 'We know what to do. The question is how to do it. Children
benefit from the experience of good early learning. But it must not be done
on the cheap, because quality counts.'
Mr Patten said half of three and four-year-olds already received some
nursery education, and if the voluntary and private sectors were included,
this rose to nine out of 10.
Labour also rejected the idea of raising the school starting age from five
to six.
</TEXT>
