FT  18 MAR 94 / Hunt offers 'partnership' to unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's trade unions were offered a new partnership with the government
yesterday by Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, but he told them they
would have 'no direct role in the determination of policy'.
Responding to last week's relaunch of the Trades Union Congress he told a
meeting of the Industrial Society that his door was 'always open for
dialogue' with the trade unions.
'But unions must recognise their own limitations,' he said. 'There will be
no preferential status for unions on the inside of government.'
The employment secretary highlighted the development of the government's
proposed new apprenticeship scheme to train about 40,000 young people a year
in technical, craft and supervisory skills as an issue on which trade unions
and government could have a dialogue.
Mr Hunt said it was 'heartening that unions may be shaping up and
modernising'. He urged them to support employers in achieving greater
competitiveness and concentrate on providing more individual services to
their members.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, welcomed employ Mr Hunt's remarks. He
said: 'It was good to hear that he and the government recognise the
potential for a positive trade union role. I do see plenty of scope for
discussion.'
Mr Monks added, however, that he was disappointed that Mr Hunt had not
acknowledged the big contribution trade unions had made to the success of 47
out of the top 50 profitable companies in Britain.
</TEXT>
