<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Watchdog agrees pensions guidelines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Securities and Invest-ments Board, the City's chief watchdog, has
completed the first stage of its work to allay public concern about the
mis-selling of personal pensions to people transferring out of an
occupational scheme.
The decision came yesterday as Legal &amp; General, the life and general
insurance group, became the latest insurer to announce that it was making
'prudent' provision against the potential need to compensate investors who
had been badly advised to transfer out of an employer's scheme.
Mr David Prosser, group chief executive, refused to give the scale of the
provisions, or say how many pension transfers L&amp;G had carried out, but said
that the overall value of pension transfers received as premiums was about
Pounds 500m.
He said the industry had been 'hit quite hard in the press' over the issue,
and suggested that the position of actuaries and occupational scheme
trustees had been somewhat overlooked so far.
At its meeting yesterday, the SIB board agreed, with only slight changes,
the proposals put forward by the regulators' steering group.
The group was set up in December to ensure higher standards in this area of
business for the future.
The main elements of the plans - which will be published shortly - are the
introduction of a cooling-off period into the pension transfer transaction
and issuing SIB guidance directly to investors about the points they should
raise with sales agents or advisers in considering a pension transfer.
The focus of SIB's work on pension transfers will now shift to compensating
people who have suffered as a result of poor advice.
By the end of next month it will issue guidance to companies about how to
identify priority cases.
This will be followed three months later by an overall plan for dealing with
past business.
L&amp;G results: Page 21
