<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Hurd drums up support over Euro-veto row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, last night addressed senior members of
the powerful backbench 1922 Committee to rally support for an eventual
compromise over Britain's demand that there should be no change to its
blocking veto.
The foreign secretary earlier received the cabinet's backing for a deal
which 'preserved the substance' of the UK position, which seeks to prevent
the number of votes needed to block legislation rising from 23 to 27. But he
was warned by Euro-sceptics that they would not vote for any deal which
'further diluted the Common's authority'.
Both Mr Hurd and the prime minister, however, have made it clear that the
dispute should not lead to a delay in enlargement of the community.
At prime minister's questions Mr John Major rebuked Mr Roger Knapman, a
Conservative Euro-sceptic, for trying to get the government to rule out any
compromise. 'I have no intention of being moved by synthetic efforts to
pressure us from any source,' he said.
He insisted that Mr Hurd was negotiating to safeguard Britain's short and
long-term interests, and added: 'I am entirely confident that can be done in
an acceptable way without any question of delaying enlargement.'
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said Mr Hurd had the
full support of his cabinet colleagues for negotiations with EU foreign
ministers on Tuesday.
He told a press conference on deregulation that he had always described
himself as a European because Britain's membership of the EU was 'a policy
extension of Britain's self-interest'. It did the UK no harm if there were
rows with Britain's partners, he said.
The government plans to bring forward legislation to the Commons in the
autumn if there is agreement on enlargement. But a number of Conservative
rightwingers and Euro-sceptics are threatening to rebel if the government
compromises over weakening its blocking veto.
Some unsuccessfully demanded that any deal by Mr Hurd should first be
discussed in the Commons.
Top business executives with experience of multinational companies should be
appointed to a special task force to tackle large-scale fraud in the
European Union, a House of Lords committee recommends today, Ivor Owen
writes.
Lord Hunt of Tamworth, chairman of the Lords committee on the European
communities, refers to a report by the Court of Auditors on the 1992 EU
budget which showed Ecu162m had been misapplied or not received. He says a
similar condemnation of international industrial or trading groups in the UK
would result in shareholders sacking the directors and appointing a new
board.
The committee calls for the task force to be established as part of urgent
remedial action co-ordinated by the council of ministers, the European
Commission and member states.
</TEXT>
