<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Cabinet deadlocked on Tube deal: Ministers warn Major to
back financing plan or risk rout in London elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major has been warned by ministerial colleagues to overrule Treasury
objections to a new London Underground financing scheme or face the threat
of a Tory rout in the London local elections in May.
The cabinet is deadlocked over a Pounds 440m leasing deal to provide new
trains for London's Northern Line. The scheme is being pressed by Mr John
MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mr John Gummer, environment secretary.
But the proposal - essentially a 20-year leasing arrangement - being
promoted by ABB Transportation, a rolling stock manufacturer, has run into
fierce Treasury opposition.
Mr Michael Portillo, the chief secretary to the Treasury, insists it would
represent a flagrant breach of public borrowing rules.
Ministers believe the deadlock will be broken only if Mr Major intervenes.
The prime minister has recently taken a tougher line in settling Whitehall
disputes and showed his willingness to overrule the Treasury when the
government last month approved London Regional Transport's CrossRail scheme.
The ministers are warning that the issue has already assumed a high
political profile because of the frequent disruption of Northern Line
services caused by the breakdown of 30-year-old trains.
The government is already bracing itself for heavy losses in outer London
boroughs in the local elections.
Ministers believe that the losses could turn into a collapse if the
government is seen to reject the modernisation plan. The scheme has won
support from a number of London-based Conservative MPs and the present
deadlock has become a powerful weapon in the Labour party's campaign. It has
secured approval from the government's own private finance panel.
Mr John Marshall, Tory MP for Hendon, yesterday used a Commons debate to
step up pressure on Mr Portillo. He said the ABB offer meant new trains
could be running on the Northern Line by Christmas.
'The Northern Line needs to be modernised and needs to be modernised
quickly,' he said. 'Any businessman would back the scheme which ABB has come
forward with.'
The government's embarrassment has been increased by the fact that Mr
Portillo has been appointed as the party's campaigns co-ordinator for the
London poll.
But the Treasury view is that the ABB proposal falls well outside its
commitment to promote private finance for important infrastructure schemes.
</TEXT>
