FT  18 MAR 94 / Malaysia urged to reverse trade bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said yesterday he hoped
Malaysia would reverse its recent discrimination against trade with British
companies, in spite of fresh indications that it was hardening its stance.
Mr Heseltine said he hoped both countries would restore good trading
relations 'at the earliest opportunity'.
His comments came as Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the Malaysian prime minister,
appeared to take a hard line towards trade relations after allegations that
a British offer of aid to help Malaysia build the Pergau dam was linked to
sales of defence equipment.
In a letter to the Financial Times, published yesterday, Dr Mahathir
attacked British press reporting on the Pergau dam issue, saying there would
be no contracts for British companies as long as 'lies' were written in the
British press about the issue.
Meanwhile, Mr Andrew Lees, campaigns director of Friends of Earth, told the
Commons foreign affairs committee yesterday that Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign
secretary, could have broken the Overseas Development Administration's rules
on aid and trade provision when he gave final approval for funds to be sent
to Malaysia in July 1991.
Mr Lees said: 'The payment in the Pergau case was not within the published
rules and procedures.' Mr Hurd could only have abided by the regulations if
he had secured Treasury permission to go ahead.
