<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Japan to ease curbs on foreign law firms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government has finalised proposals to ease restrictions on the
freedom of foreign lawyers to do business in Japan.
Under plans prepared by the Justice Ministry, and due to take effect within
a year, foreign and Japanese law firms would be allowed to merge and to
practise foreign and Japanese law from the same office. At present, clients
have to go to separate legal offices for advice on foreign and national law.
However, Japanese lawyers have managed to persuade the government to let
them keep up some protectionism, in the form of a continued ban on foreign
lawyers arguing Japanese cases in Japanese courts.
The proposals are expected to be laid before parliament early next month and
should come into force early in 1995.
They are the result of longstanding pressure from the European Union and the
US, keen to have access to Japan's lucrative but tightly controlled legal
market.
The Japan Federation of Bar Associations has been understandably very
reluctant to expose itself to competition from foreign firms.
However, it finally decided to compromise with the Justice Ministry after Mr
Morihiro Hosokawa, the prime minister, seized on the proposals as part of
his drive for more deregulation in the country's protectionist economy.
</TEXT>
