<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Brazil will tackle debt restructuring without IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil told leading bank creditors yesterday it intends to try to complete
its Dollars 52bn commercial debt restructuring by an April 15 deadline
rather than wait for formal support from the International Monetary Fund,
which is not expected until later this year.
Mr Paulo Tarso Flecha de Lima, Brazil's ambassador in Washington, confirmed
his country was seeking to complete the deal without the IMF. 'It will be
difficult but not impossible. We're confident,' he said.
The initiative follows the IMF's refusal on Wednesday to grant Brazil a
standby loan until its planned anti-inflation reforms are in place. If the
country's bank creditors agree to go ahead, Brazil would be the first large
country to launch a Brady-type debt restructuring without the backing of an
IMF standby loan.
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, finance minister, held talks yesterday with Mr
William Rhodes, vice chairman of Citibank, closing agents for the deal, to
discuss going ahead without the IMF.
Brazil is running out of time and must give notification by tonight that the
April 15 deadline will be met and old debt swapped for new. This deadline
has already been extended and bankers said it could be stretched further.
Before Brazil can give notification, the banks need to agree a waiver of the
restructuring's original requirement for IMF backing. Leading banks met
yesterday to discuss a waiver, which was described as 'do-able' by one
banker. Mr Rhodes said a decision on the waiver would be ready this
afternoon.
Brazil also needs to find an acceptable guarantee for the deal. Originally
the US Treasury was set to issue up to Dollars 21.5bn of zero coupon bonds
as part of a guarantee once the IMF standby was secured. It is unclear if
enough bonds are available. Going ahead with the restructuring without the
IMF would make the deal more expensive and risky. It also would deprive Mr
Cardoso, a potential presidential candidate, of the kudos of IMF backing.
Mr Cardoso had hoped to persuade the IMF to agree a letter of intent for the
stand-by loan during meetings on Wednesday. Although the IMF was supportive,
it did not commit itself to granting the stand-by. It is thought to have
insisted Brazil ran a budget surplus this year but Brazil was only prepared
to offer a balanced budget.
The IMF has also grown wary of Brazil, which has signed but failed to
deliver on eight letters of intent and two stand-by agreements in the last
12 years. Brazil's decision to go ahead without the IMF maybe seen as a
snub, but the country is in an unusual position. It has foreign reserves of
more than Dollars 30bn and IMF support would have been largely symbolic.
Success for Mr Cardoso's domestic reforms, mainly designed to tackle annual
inflation of about 2,500 per cent, is seen as more important for his
presidential ambitions. But Mr Cardoso also wanted the IMF letter and a
smooth conclusion to the bank deal. According to finance ministry officials,
he will now use the IMF's supportive comments as 'the best possible
endorsement' given that the economic reform programme is still unproven.
</TEXT>
<XX>
