<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 94 / Italy reins in budget deficit: Economic Watch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Rome
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's budget deficit fell by 3.3 per cent last year but was still
marginally higher than forecast at L153,539bn (Pounds 62bn). This compares
with a projection of L151,200bn and the previous year's L158,840bn.
Excluding interest payments on the rising debt stock, there was a surplus
close to 2 per cent of gross domestic product. Although austerity measures
to contain public borrowing were the harshest applied by any EU member, the
deficit still represented almost 10 per cent of GDP. Italy is committed to
bring the deficit within Maastricht convergence criteria to around
L106,000bn (5.8 per cent of GDP) by 1996. The 1994 budget envisages a
deficit of about L151,000bn.
Consumer prices in the Netherlands rose 0.5 per cent in February from the
previous month and were 3 per cent higher than a year earlier. Excluding
indirect taxes, the February consumer price index was up 2.5 per cent from a
year earlier and 0.6 per cent up from January.
Swedish consumer prices rose 0.3 per cent in February, and 1.9 per cent
since February last year.
</TEXT>
