<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / International Company News: Aldus and Adobe set to merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Aldus and Adobe Systems, two pioneers of desktop publishing software, are to
merge in a stock swap deal valued at about Dollars 525m. Combined, the
companies have annual revenues of about Dollars 520m.
Adobe will exchange 1.15 shares of its common stock for each share of Aldus
common stock.
Aldus' share price rose sharply yesterday on news of the merger agreement,
trading at Dollars 31 1/8 , up from Tuesday's close of Dollars 26 1/4 .
Adobe Systems was trading at Dollars 28 3/4 , down from Dollars 32 1/2 .
'We believe our two companies, each with a rich history of inventing
different aspects of the electronic publishing revolution, are simply much
stronger together - both technologically and financially,' said Mr John
Warnock, chairman and chief executive of Adobe Systems.
Adobe and Aldus are widely recognised for having created 'desktop
publishing' - the use of personal computers in publishing newsletters,
magazines and newspapers. Over the past decade publishing software has grown
into a Dollars 2bn industry.
Adobe's flagship product is PostScript, a computer language for printers
that has become an industry standard. It also makes programs that allow
computer users to print text in various typefaces.
Based in Mountain View, California, the company reported fiscal 1993
revenues of Dollars 313m and net income of Dollars 57m.
Aldus' leading product is PageMaker, a program for the 'lay out' or design
of documents such as magazine pages. Based in Seattle, Washington, it had
1993 revenues of Dollars 207m and net income of Dollars 9.5m.
The companies' products are complementary, with little overlap, analysts
said. Mr Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies, a California market
research firm, said the deal would allow them 'to be much more of a
powerhouse when it comes to next-generation desktop publishing, printing and
graphics technology'.
</TEXT>
