<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / International Company News: Publishing side boosts Thomson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Record earnings from publishing and UK travel helped Thomson Corporation
overcome the poor performance of its North American newspapers last year.
Net earnings of the Canadian-controlled company rose to USDollars 277m, or
48 cents a share, from Dollars 166m, or 30 cents, in 1992. Revenues slipped
to Dollars 5.85bn from Dollars 5.98bn.
Last year's results include a fourth-quarter Dollars 75m after-tax charge
for the restructuring of Thomson's North American papers, especially the
five biggest dailies with circulations of over 75,000 copies. The
performance of these five papers, the biggest of which is Canada's Globe and
Mail, has lagged that of the group's smaller titles.
In 1992, Thomson's newspaper interests took a Dollars 170m charge, mainly
reflecting the reduced value of its UK community papers, most of which were
sold or closed.
Thomson Travel's operating earnings rose to Dollars 115m last year from
Dollars 104m. The improvement was dampened, however, by the drop in sterling
against the US dollar. The company said that the start of the summer 1994
booking season has been 'exceptionally strong', with bookings up 47 per cent
on the same time last year.
A Thomson official expressed the hope that the overall buoyancy in the UK
travel market would prevent any large-scale tour discounting this year. The
Lunn Poly travel-shop chain increased its market share of summer tours last
year. But the cost of opening 127 new shops pushed down profits.
Information and publishing results soared to Dollars 358m from Dollars 249m.
The recovery of UK regional newspapers gathered pace in the second half of
1993, although circulations of daily titles remained under pressure.
In the US, a strong performance by scientific and medical data services
helped overcome a 'severe' decline in pharmaceutical advertising and
automotive collision repair data.
Thomson, which is moving its executive offices from New York to Connecticut,
announced a split in its fast-growing specialised information and publishing
division.
The division will be separated into financial and professional publishing,
with annual revenues of Dollars 1bn; and a business, education and
information group, which will include the UK regional newspapers.
</TEXT>
