<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Sheikh buys Nordic oil group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES and ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Nordic region's biggest oil refining group, OK Petroleum, was yesterday
sold to Sheikh Mohammed Al-Amoudi, a Saudi Arabian businessman, for Dollars
1.2bn (Pounds 820m) including debt.
The deal illustrates a growing trend for state-owned oil companies from
petroleum exporting countries to buy downstream assets in Europe, Asia and
the US. But the OK sale is being carried out through a private company,
Corral Petroleum Holdings.
Equity proceeds of Dollars 750m will be split between OK's three owners: the
Swedish state (24 per cent), the KF co-operative group (52 per cent) and
Neste, the Finnish oil company (24 per cent). The sale furthers the Swedish
government's privatisation programme and allows KF and Neste to concentrate
on core and majority-owned businesses. Kleinwort Benson acted for all three
sellers.
The Saudi link should provide the group with strong financial backing for
further investment. 'Our intention is that OK Petroleum should grow within
its current area of operation,' said Mr Ghazi Habib, who will represent the
sheikh on the OK board. Mr Habib is a former head of Samarec, the Saudi
refining and crude marketing company which was merged with Saudi Aramco last
year.
OK, which will retain its Swedish base and management has two refineries on
Sweden's west coast, with a combined refining capacity of 265,000 barrels a
day. It accounts for 23 per cent of the Nordic refining capacity, and around
60 per cent of output is exported.
The deal also includes storage facilities, ownership stakes in several
hundred retailing outlets and some upstream operations. It excludes around
650 OK petrol stations which are owned independently.
OK Petroleum was founded in 1986 by a consortium including Neste. Last year
net profits rose to SKr552m (Pounds 47m) from SKr41m while sales increased
to SKr19.5bn from SKr16.0bn.
Sheik Al-Amoudi, a member of a merchant family from Jeddah, has not
previously been involved in the oil industry, although he has had business
dealings in Sweden for more than 20 years, including involvement with the
construction company ABV.
Mr Alan Marshall, oil analyst with Swiss Bank Corp in London, said he
expected that the buyers would use OK Petroleum to build market share in
Scandinavia and Europe. 'This will make life tougher for established
players,' he predicted.
</TEXT>
