<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / France forces retreat on fish prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A late-night French threat to block Norway's entry into the European Union
produced a rapid pay-off for Paris early yesterday with Brussels announcing
a two-month extension of minimum prices for fish imported into the EU.
France's strong-arm tactics forced a U-turn by the European Commission which
24 hours earlier had refused to extend crisis measures to prop up fish
prices.
The Commission's retreat will upset fish exporters in the US and eastern
Europe, but offers a breathing space to the French government, which has
struggled to contain violent protests by its fishermen against cheap
imports.
Mr Alain Lamassoure, French minister for European affairs, said he had
intervened with Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission,
during a marathon negotiating session on Norwegian accession to the EU which
ended early yesterday.
'I made it quite clear this was a condition for our agreement to Norwegian
membership, and especially on the fish arrangements with Norway,' he said.
The French threat succeeded, and shortly before midnight Norway and the EU
reached agreement on fishing rights.
A final accord on the terms of entry for Sweden, Finland, Austria and Norway
remains elusive, however, because of Anglo-Spanish objections to
power-sharing arrangements in an expanded union.
Minimum import prices will apply to imports of cod, haddock, hake, angler,
coley, Alaskan pollack and salmon.
The decision to extend minimum import prices will come into effect this week
and apply until May 17. It will be reviewed at a meeting of European Union
fisheries ministers in Luxembourg on April 12.
</TEXT>
