<DATE>940317
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: Schroders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Now that Schroders has taken the plunge on disclosure it turns out that the
company does indeed have much to boast about. Not only did profits rise 85
per cent last year; the quality is good too. Schroders is much less reliant
than some of its competitors on dealing income. Fee income accounts for
almost two-thirds of operating income. Schroders has been continuing to win
new fund management business since the start of the year. That should help
offset any fall in its income caused by weakness in financial markets. There
must be more venture capital gains in the pipeline, although the timing is
uncertain.
Even without any increase in profits, Schroders would be on a forward
multiple of less than 11 times. If that makes the shares seem good value,
one is left agape at the 6.6 times dividend cover. There is clearly minimal
constraint on dividend progression.
But such high earnings retentions when the company already has surplus
capital are where the strategic questions begin. A 23 per cent return on
capital might seem low at this stage in the cycle, though Schroders is
barely geared and its profits are less volatile than those of other merchant
banks. Arguably Schroders missed an opportunity to enhance its return by
buying back its own shares when the price was cheaper. It cannot accumulate
capital for ever. The worry is that it may do something just to ease the
discomfort. However, it has a record of getting the strategic decisions
right.
</TEXT>
