<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Film industry campaigns for levy on distributors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British film makers yesterday launched a campaign to persuade the government
to impose a voluntary levy on film distributors backed by a series of tax
breaks in order to rejuvenate the industry.
Supported by actors such as Michael Caine and producers David Puttnam and
Jeremy Thomas the 'Impact' campaign argues that money from cinema, video and
pay-television distributors should be transferred to British film-making in
return for tax breaks.
Mr Tom Gutteridge, chairman of Pact, the main film and television producers'
organisation, said that modest changes could lead to Pounds 220m a year in
extra finance for the industry and would cost the government nothing after
two years. 'We are not looking for additional government subsidy,' he said.
'Our plans are going to make money for Britain.'
The main suggestion is that all those who distribute films in the UK would
be assessed and then encouraged to spend a small percentage of qualifying
revenues  - probably around 1 per cent  - on British film-making.
In return they would be able to get a 100 per cent write-off on the
investment in the first year. At the moment film investment is written off
over three years.
Impact believes this measure could generate Pounds 60m a year of new
production finance for the industry. A further Pounds 160m could be raised
if the first-year tax deduction available to all British films was increased
to 65 per cent.
The National Heritage Department helped to fund a study by Hydra/Olsberg,
strategy consultants for Pact which provided most of the Impact proposals.
To make the scheme more flexible for the distributors, this study suggested
the creation of Film Depository Receipts which they would receive after
promising to help finance British films.
The FDRs could be combined from different sources to finance a single film
and would be a flexible means of attracting the special tax concessions for
the distributors.
'If the system we propose were introduced then the effect would be to
revitalise the UK production base without denting the profitability of the
investors involved,' Mr Gutteridge said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
