<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Local councils to demand more parishes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government will today be urged to create more parishes as part of its
review of local government.
The National Association of Local Councils, which represents community,
parish and town councils, says that about 13m people in rural England
effectively have a 'three-tier' local government system of counties,
districts and parishes. Parish and equivalent councils are served by 75,000
councillors.
Merging counties and districts would mean that in 'unparished' areas
(without a parish, town or community council) local government would become
more distant, they say. Residents would have only one tier to complain to if
they faced problems.
Parish councils celebrate their centenary this year, and will attempt to use
the anniversary, coupled with the review, to raise the profile of their tier
of government.
Several counties, including Oxfordshire and Surrey, are also exploring ways
of devolving power to local councils, thereby doing away with the
district-level tier.
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, has urged that local government
reform work on the 'subsidiarity' principle, whereby all powers are devolved
to the lowest practical level. However, the legislation that started the
review does not allow transfers of functions and responsibilities between
the tiers.
Mr Martin Harvey, the NALC's deputy secretary, said that if subsidiarity was
to be implemented properly, counties or districts should make agency
agreements with parishes to deliver specific services  - such as local
libraries  - which are currently a county responsibility.
He also said that subsidiarity would require separate entries for parish
councils in government grants. At present, parishes gain all their funding
from the grant paid to district councils, which are then expected to hand
funds on parishes.
At present, the association claims, local councillors do not draw expenses
for work inside parishes or communities, and many council clerks work
part-time. According to its estimates, parishes now only account for 0.3 per
cent of total local government spending.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
