<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / London role as world city 'threatened'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
By John Willman,
Public Policy Editor
London's future as a world city has been weakened by the absence of a single
planning authority for the central business district, says Hillier Parker,
the firm of estate agents.
The 10 London boroughs responsible for planning in inner London have
designated less than half the central business area as part of the Central
Activities Zone where priority will be given to business and economic
development.
The London Planning Advisory Committee will today present its latest advice
to the government on how to develop the capital. The committee, which
represents all London local authorities, is expected to emphasise the
importance of the Central Activities Zone in London's continued success as a
world city.
Planners traditionally use the registrar-general's definition of London's
central business area  - which is based on demographic data revealing where
property is mainly non-residential (see map). However, much of this area has
been left outside the central activities zone as defined by the 10 boroughs.
This includes all of the central business area in the three boroughs on the
south bank of the Thames  - Wandsworth, Lambeth and Southwark. Islington,
which adjoins the City financial district, has designated only one small
area as part of the zone.
'Each of the 10 boroughs covering central London can say it has made
provision for business development,' says Mr John Parmiter of Hillier
Parker.
'But overall the picture is of a city that is shrinking and becoming more
fragmented in planning terms.'
As a result, London will find it harder to attract international businesses
to the capital, says Mr Parmiter.
Other European cities, such as Paris and Frankfurt, have single local
authorities that offer attractive packages to inward investors.
'Some of these boroughs appear to regard their central London areas as
distractions from their responsibilities to residents,' says Mr Parmiter.
'There is no agreement between them on what constitutes the central
activities zone. Camden excludes all but a small part of its area while
neighbouring Westminster casts the net far wider.'
Since the abolition of the Greater London Council in 1986, responsibility
for planning in central London has been divided between nine inner-city
boroughs and the City Corporation.
Each is completing its first unitary development plan setting out strategic
planning policies on matters such as areas to be designated for business
development. Little effort has been made to co-ordinate the 10 plans, says
Mr Parmiter.
Comparison of the 10 maps shows that neighbouring boroughs disagree on such
matters as the line of the underground railway and the route for new lines
such as CrossRail. Most of the boroughs' plans for the central area are too
advanced to be altered significantly.
</TEXT>
