</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Local councils to demand more parishes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government will today be urged to create more parishes as part of its
review of local government.
The National Association of Local Councils, which represents community,
parish and town councils, says that about 13m people in rural England
effectively have a 'three-tier' local government system of counties,
districts and parishes. Parish and equivalent councils are served by 75,000
councillors.
Merging counties and districts would mean that in unparished areas, local
government would become more distant, and residents would only have one tier
to complain to in the event of problems.
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, has urged that local government
reform work on the 'subsidiarity' principle, where all powers are devolved
to the lowest practical level. However, the legislation that started the
review does not allow transfers of functions and responsibilities between
the tiers.
Mr Martin Harvey, the NALC's deputy secretary, said that if subsidiarity was
to be implemented properly, counties or districts should make agency
agreements with parishes to deliver specific services - such as local
libraries - which are currently a county responsibility.
He also said that subsidiarity would require separate entries for parish
councils in government grants. At present, parishes gain all their funding
from the grant paid to district councils, who are then expected to devolve
funds to parishes.
Local authorities have started intensive lobbying of Labour MPs over the
local government review.
The MPs are in a pivotal position after dissension among Tories. In the past
week the Labour leaders of 38 English and Welsh counties have called on the
party to drop its support for the review, claiming it will be a 'political
disaster' and will 'only weaken local government further by replacing
county-wide strategic services with joint boards and quangos'.
But the leaders of more than 100 Labour-led district councils have also
written to all Labour MPs urging them not to abandon the party's policy of
strong support for unitary councils that combine the functions carried out
at present by districts and counties. The letter says that MORI polls
carried out for the Local Government Commission showed a general majority of
two-to-one among voters in favour of the unitary principle.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, backs unitary authorities, and
said in a recent interview with the Municipal Journal that the party had
favoured unitary local government 'forever'. However, this approach is
deeply unpopular with the Association of County Councils, which has been
Labour-controlled. Some Labour spokesmen are now uncomfortable with this
line.
</TEXT>
