<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Confusion clouds labour statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The headline fall in February's seasonally adjusted unemployment total may
be good news  - but the detailed statistics published yesterday by the
Department of Employment display some confused signals of the strength of
the labour market.
One pattern which had been noticed during 1993 was that new jobs being
created were mostly part-time, and mostly for women. But some of the
department's figures appear to show that that trend has reversed.
The figures for employees in employment (collected from employers) show that
full-time employment rose by 19,000 between September and December, while
part-time employment fell by 5,000. However, the Labour Force Survey  - a
survey of 60,000 households  - seems to show the opposite.
The survey says that, between the summer and the autumn of 1993, part-time
employment rose by 90,000, while full-time employment fell by 17,000.
Although the statistics cover slightly different periods, the contradiction
is apparent.
The department's figures also show that, in the last three months of 1993,
the main cause of a 15,000 increase in people in employment came from a rise
in the self-employed.
The number of self-employed rose by 54,000, cancelling out a 52,000 fall in
the number of people in employment. An extra 23,000 people were on
work-related government training programmes, while 9,000 fewer were employed
in the armed forces.
The growth in self-employment has been fairly erratic, showing a 75,000 jump
between March and June 1993, but being virtually flat in the third quarter
of last year.
Some caveats also apply to the 38,800 fall  - to 2.75m  - in seasonally
adjusted unemployment in February. The employment department has changed the
seasonal adjustment for February. Under the old seasonal adjustment, the
figures would have shown a fall of just 18,800. The unadjusted total fell by
47,855 to 2.84m.
Furthermore, January's unexpected rise in unemployment has been revised
upwards, from 15,500 to 19,800. Manufacturing employment continues to fall,
recording a 13,000 drop in January. And vacancies at job centres increased
by only 400 in February, compared with an average monthly increase of 2,100
over the past six months.
Nevertheless, there were several good signs. The number of people joining
the unemployment register, at a seasonally adjusted 324,700, was the lowest
monthly figure since October 1990. The number of working days lost due to
industrial disputes in January was 2,000.
Overtime working in the manufacturing sector rose by 0.33m hours to 9.29m
hours per week in January, while short-time working fell slightly to 0.25m
hours per week.
Unemployment fell in all regions in February, for both men and women. East
Anglia has the lowest percentage of workforce unemployed, at 7.8 per cent.
With the south-west and the north, it has seen the biggest percentage drop
since January.
The north has the highest percentage of unemployment apart from Northern
Ireland, which has 13.2 per cent.
The Labour Force Survey shows that 205,000 people were made redundant in the
three months before its survey, a fall of 32,000 compared with the summer
1993 survey.
The survey continues to show an unemployment figure 57,000 higher than that
compiled from benefit claimants. According to the survey 24.9m people were
in employment in the autumn of last year.
