<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Scottish unemployment forecast to exceed 10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unemployment in Scotland, which fell 0.1 per cent in February to 9.3 per
cent, was yesterday predicted to rise to 10.1 per cent by the end of the
year.
The rise will come as companies responded to increasing price competition by
shedding permanent staff and making more use of overtime, says the
prediction, which comes from the Fraser of Allander Institute of Strathclyde
University, Scotland's main economic forecaster.
It implies that Scotland will have a slightly higher unemployment rate
during recovery than it experienced during the recent recession. Seasonally
adjusted unemployment peaked early last year at 9.9 per cent.
The institute believes that the number of people employed will fall by about
20,000 by the end of 1994, with service industries losing 11,000 jobs and
manufacturing shedding between 4,500 and 5,000 jobs.
The institute says falls in employment are not matched by equivalent rises
in registered unemployment, possibly because of people going into part-time
work, or retiring.
It expects unemployment to rise by about 5,000 by the end of the year. The
unemployment rate will fall again in 1995 as output increases further.
Manufacturing output, which grew by 2.2 per cent in 1993, should rise by 3.3
per cent in 1994.
While the Scottish economy would benefit from improved export prospects and
lower interest rates, the benefits would be offset by the effect of value
added tax on heating bills and proportionately greater curbs on public
expenditure.
Quarterly Economic Bulletin March 1994. Fraser of Allander Institute, 100
Cathedral Street, Glasgow G4 0LN. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
