<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Rise in rate of average earnings causes concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An increase in the annual growth rate of average earnings  - the first rise
since February 1992  - raised fears that a long period of subdued wage rises
might be over.
The underlying annual increase in earnings in the 12 months to January was
3.25 per cent. This was the same as the revised figure for December, which
had previously been announced as 3 per cent. The annual growth rate had been
steadily declining since the 7.5 per cent recorded in February 1992.
In the manufacturing and production sectors, underlying earnings rose 4.5
per cent in the 12 months to January, up from 4.25 per cent in December.
The increase in service-sector earnings in the year to January was 3 per
cent, up from 2.75 per cent in December and the third consecutive monthly
rise.
The Department of Employment estimates the underlying rise in earnings by
making adjustments for other influences such as pay arrears and variations
in the timing of settlements.
The actual increase in earnings in the year to January was 3.6 per cent.
The department said there was little evidence of an increase in the general
level of pay settlements, so the most likely explanation for the rise was
increased bonus payments.
Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist at SG Warburg Securities, said: 'As the trend
cannot easily be explained, and given the weakness elsewhere in the labour
market, it is hard to get too concerned at this stage. The uptrend will not
be strong.'
Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist at Salomon Brothers International, said:
'The rise in average earnings is not yet large enough to threaten the
inflation outlook. It is only if the rise is a step on the way up to a level
between 4 per cent and 5 per cent that it poses problems to the low
inflation outlook. As yet, there is no sign that wage deals are rising that
sharply.'
The rise in earnings meant that unit labour costs have also increased. In
the year to January wages and salaries per unit of output in the
manufacturing sector rose by 1.7 per cent, compared with 1 per cent in the
year to December.
In the three months to January unit wage costs in the manufacturing sector
were 1.3 per cent higher than in the same three months a year ago.
Productivity is still improving, however. Output per head rose by 3 per cent
in the year to January, compared with 2.9 per cent in the 12 months to
December.
</TEXT>
