The MPs said they would refuse to recommend the privatisation to the Commons
until they received 'much more convincing' assurances about the laboratory's
independence. The report is a severe blow to Mr John MacGregor, the
transport secretary, who has said that privatisation is 'a feasible option'.
The government will also be embarrassed by disclosures in the report that
the committee's strong line was prompted by Mr Peter Bottomley, Conservative
MP for Eltham and a former transport minister.
Mr Bottomley joined the Labour minority on the seven-strong committee to
amend a resolution criticising the privatisation proposals to make it clear
that they lacked justification.
The committee also drew the government's attention to evidence given by the
Association of Chief Police Officers which suggested that privatisation
would reduce safety standards on Britain's roads.
Privatisation of the laboratory, which advises the Department of Transport
and other customers on transport issues, was recommended by an inquiry
carried out for Mr MacGregor by KPMG Corporate Finance. The inquiry said
that the retention of the laboratory in the public sector 'would risk it
being unable to respond adequately to changes in its market' and would
present a 'considerable risk' of a cycle of cumulative decline.
</TEXT>
