<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Inter-party row deepens over council tax levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative and Labour politicians were yesterday engaged in an
increasingly bitter spat over the amount of council tax to be levied by
local authorities. Signs that the issue will dominate campaigning for May's
local elections have fuelled the row.
Ministers again accused Labour authorities of 'waste, mismanagment and
inefficiency', arguing that they would charge more than their Tory
counterparts in each of the council tax's eight property bands. Labour tried
to shoot down the Tories' figures, claiming that they were 'spurious' and
that the only sensible comparison of council tax levels was to be found in
the average council tax per dwelling. These figures show Labour councils
charging less than the Tories and Liberal Democrats.
Sides paraded their different claims in the House of Commons yesterday
afternoon.
Mr David Curry, local government minister, said that he could think of no
less sensible way of expressing the payments than an average, 'be-cause
nobody pays an average tax'. He added: 'Whether you are with modest means
and a modest house, whether you have got a middle-income and a middle-band
house, or even if you are relatively well off in Band H, you are always
paying less under Conservative than you do under Labour or under Liberal
Democrat councils.'
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, said that both the Department
of the Environment and Tory central office had used average figures in March
last year when setting out the impact of the tax.
'Did central office use those figures before they discovered that average
household council tax bills per dwelling are Pounds 40 lower in Labour areas
than they are in Conservative areas?' asked Mr Straw.
A Labour official said yesterday that the council tax issue was one on which
his party was unlikely to win. But he said the aim of Labour's campaign was
to ensure that the government did not score an easy victory.
Councils demand, Page 11
</TEXT>
