<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Bus group rages at 'naive OFT'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading yesterday ruled that Fife Scottish Omnibuses, a
subsidiary of the quoted bus company Stagecoach, had 'preyed on' a rival by
registering loss-making commercial services on routes where the other
company operated subsidised services.
Fife Scottish immediately accused the OFT of naivety and said its report
contained 'inaccuracies, half-truths and outright misrepresentation'.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said he was satisfied
that Fife Scottish's behaviour was predatory and that its intention was to
displace its rival, Moffat &amp; Williamson, the Fife company which brought the
complaint.
Fife Scottish said the complaint concerned only six services and that those
services had come to an end last August, before the OFT inquiry began.
Stagecoach operates subsidiaries in many parts of Britain and its
subsidiaries have frequently been subject to investigations by the OFT. Some
of these have resulted in the companies giving undertakings to the OFT.
Mr Jim Moffat, Fife Scottish's managing director, said he was concerned that
'a supposedly impartial body could come up with such a mish-mash of
inaccuracies, half-truths and outright misrepresentation of the facts and
background of this case'.
He accused the OFT of ignoring what Fife Scottish had told it. 'The naivety
of the OFT continues to surprise me and some of the financial reasoning in
this report is quite ludicrous in the context of bus operations,' he said.
The OFT said last night that the fact that the services complained of no
longer operated was immaterial. It would be seeking undertakings from Fife
Scottish that it would not register loss-making services on subsidised
routes in the future. If it did not receive such undertakings the issue
would be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
It could not comment on Fife Scottish's views on its report.
Mr Derek Scott, finance director of Stagecoach, said that the issue was not
of material importance either to Stagecoach or to Fife Scottish, which has
an annual turnover of Pounds 17m.
Moffat &amp; Williamson welcomed the report.
