<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Crossed Lamont stops ex-chequer Healey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Never again will Lord Healey's finger be extended for a sympathetic shop
assistant to hang a wrapped CD from it. No longer will the former chancellor
walk out of a record shop and flinch at the sight of a Thresher's
off-licence.
A campaign of television commercials for debit cards starring the Labour
elder statesman has been scrapped by The Independent Television Commission
after it received a complaint from Mr Norman Lamont, a former Conservative
chancellor.
The commercials illustrate making purchases without cheques and are
accompanied by billboard posters describing Lord Healey as an 'ex-chequer'.
On television, he buys a CD, potters into the street and confronts the
Thresher's sign. The voiceover says that the Visa Delta debit card is so
simple that even chancellors of the exchequer can understand it. Newspaper
reports last year alleged that Mr Lamont had bought wine and cigarettes at a
particular branch of the Thresher's off-licence chain with his credit card.
Mr Lamont is not referred to in the Healey commercial, but the commission
said: 'He clearly believed (the advertisement) referred to him, and other
people agreed with him.'
Asked about the advertisement at Westminster yesterday, Mr Lamont said: 'The
whole Thresher incident was a lie and a fabrication of certain newspapers. I
do not see why a lie should be perpetuated in an advertisement.'
The ITC said it upheld Mr Lamont's complaint because the advertisement
breached its rules on privacy. Under the ITC's code permission has to be
sought from individuals portrayed.
Visa International said yesterday the advertising campaign had been 'highly
successful in improving cardholder understanding of Visa Delta' and was only
intended to run until yesterday.
</TEXT>
