<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Greater changes to NHS urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Too much rust remains in the mechanism of the government's National Health
Service reforms and further changes are needed, the free-market Adam Smith
Institute argues today.
The reforms have led to gains but the institute's report says that old
relationships between purchasers and providers had been carried into the new
system and many of the same personalities were running the service.
The institute calls for district health authorities to be turned into fully
independent provident trusts, competing with fundholding general
practitioners for the right to purchase health care. This would provide
patients with freedom of choice and there was no reason why many aspects of
purchasing, including the assessment of local needs, could not eventually be
contracted out to non-public agencies.
GP fundholders, suggests the report, are likely to lead a movement of
structural change away from hospitals, with far more services provided in
community clinics. But much of the capital to finance such a shift would
have to come from the private sector.
The institute says: 'With a decade of experience behind us, it is time to
acknowledge the savings in time and money derived from employing private
sector management skills on infrastructure projects far outweigh any derived
from the idea that the government can always borrow more cheaply.
Fundholders have to be allowed full access to private sector capital.'
Unhealthy Competition, Adam Smith Institute, Pounds 30
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9431 Administration of Public Health Programs.
    P80   Health Services.
</IN>
<XX>
