<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / MPs question PIA's standing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs on the cross-party Treasury committee yesterday expressed doubts that
the new investor protection watchdog would inspire public confidence.
Taking evidence from Lautro, the existing regulator for the life insurance
industry, MPs highlighted the role of Mr Joe Palmer, chairman of the new
personal investment authority.
Mr Brian Sedgemore, a Labour committee member, asked whether Mr Palmer
should be seen in the category of people of the highest quality on whom the
regulatory system depended.
Legal &amp; General, the life insurance company where Mr Palmer was formerly
chief executive, recently attracted a record fine from Lautro for a
widespread and systemic failure to meet regulators' requirements.
Mr Barry Sherlock, Lautro chairman, said that the important issue was the
way in which a company dealt with weaknesses that had been identified.
He said: 'As a result of the work we have done over the last five years, no
single company has a totally clear record.'
He admitted but sought to minimise the risk that the PIA might find it
difficult to establish public confidence, emphasising instead the progress
made in setting up the PIA since Mr Palmer had been appointed.
Mr Giles Radice, another Labour committee member, suggested that the PIA
might find taking on staff from existing regulators a barrier to creating
confidence.
Mr Sherlock said existing staff were skilled and experienced. Without them
the PIA would be 'a disaster'.
Asked why it took so long to agree on disclosure of the commission on life
insurance products, Mr Sherlock cited the need to work with the Securities
and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog.
</TEXT>
