<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / IMF slow to act on Brazil loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Monetary Fund yesterday welcomed Brazil's economic reform
efforts, but fell short of promising a stand-by loan to back the
government's anti-inflation programme.
This left unclear the status of the country's commercial bank debt
restructuring, which needs an IMF seal of approval and is close to a
deadline.
Mr Michel Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, said there was already a
'significant record of progress' in tackling Brazil's annual inflation of
about 2,500 per cent under Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, finance minister.
He said Mr Cardoso's plans to introduce a new currency later this year
should lead to a 'sharp reduction' in inflation. The IMF has proposed a
monitored economic programme to be followed, when the new currency is
introduced, by either a stand-by loan agreement or a 'form of enhanced
co-operation'. He said work was continuing on the Brazilian programme for
'early consideration' by the IMF executive board.
Mr Camdessus made no committment on the signing or timing of a letter of
intent for the stand-by loan accord.
According to some analysts, such a letter is thought to be needed before the
US Treasury agrees to issue zero coupon bonds. These will form part of the
guarantee for the Brady-style rescheduling of Brazil's Dollars 52bn (Pounds
35.60bn) of private commerical bank debt.
Under the existing timetable, the bank deal has to be finalised by April 15.
Bankers and Brazilian officials had hoped the IMF would indicate support for
the deal this week. Delaying the April deadline is possible but difficult.
Mr Cardoso said he thought the IMF's statement, which listed eight positive
aspects of the country's economic policy for this year, was enough to win
support from the US Treasury.
Mr Cardoso is today due to meet Mr William Rhodes, vice-chairman of
Citibank, the closing agent for the bank deal, to discuss the next moves.
Notification that the deal is to go ahead has to be given by Friday for the
April 15 deadline to be met.
Brazil may now try to use Mr Camdessus' statement as an intention of support
and go ahead with the debt rescheduling without the formal stand-by loan
agreement. This would require the banks granting a waiver this week, and
would also suggest Brazil has already bought at least some of the required
zero coupon bonds in the market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
