<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Paraguay peasants in protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Paraguayan peasants have staged the biggest demonstration in the capital
Asuncion since President Juan Carlos Wasmosy took office seven months ago.
The peasants demanded land reform and protested at low prices for cotton,
one of their staple products.
About 15,000-20,000 peasants crammed into one of the capital's main squares
in front of the Congress building on Tuesday, while their leader, Mr Alfonso
Cohene, met opposition leaders to demand the expropriation of unproductive
land. He also demanded government subsidies to offset the decline in cotton
prices.
The peasants were unable to petition President Wasmosy because he was on an
official visit to Brazil. No one was reported hurt in the protest, despite
police efforts to prevent protesters reaching Asuncion.
Last month police clashed several times with peasants in the interior of the
country after protesters blocked roads and occupied farmland owned by
wealthy landowners, including one property owned by a senior member of the
ruling Colorado party.
Over half of Paraguay's population of 4.5m lives in the countryside, often
in great poverty. Demands for land reform have always been an important
issue, although the 35-year regime of former President Alfredo Stroessner
crushed simmering opposition.
