<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Enlargement of EU strains Franco-German axis: Anxiety in
Paris over the future of the Union has led to criticism of 'heavy-handed'
tactics by Bonn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The close diplomatic and political ties between Paris and Bonn,
traditionally regarded as the principal motor of European integration, have
come under new strain because of French concerns at the whole process of
enlargement of the European Union, according to senior government officials.
Criticism of Germany's allegedly heavy-handed tactics in forcing the pace of
the enlargement negotiations in Brussels emerged in Bonn yesterday, causing
anger and alarm in the office of Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
'We are urgently trying to contain the damage,' one German official said
yesterday.
The French concerns over EU enlargement include a worry about the inclusion
of a strong free trade lobby with the new northern members, and fear that
community institutions will be made both weaker and more cumbersome with
rapid enlargement to eastern Europe.
Publication of a long and detailed critique of German foreign policy in the
prestigious Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, quoting French sources in the
German capital, has clearly come at an acutely embarrassing time for the
German chancellor, who has just launched a highly personalised campaign for
re-election.
Mr Kohl is basing his appeal to German voters, both in the forthcoming
European elections, and in the general election in October, on his record as
a staunch proponent of European integration, and the guarantor of good
relations with major powers like France, Britain, the US and Russia. Any
suggestion that his closest ally, France, is dissatisfied with the
relationship is seen by senior German officials as extremely unhelpful.
The article is the latest in a series of diplomatic upsets, including
uncertainty over whether the German leader should be invited to the 50th
anniversary celebrations of the D-Day landings in Normandy, and cancellation
of the Allied military parades planned to mark withdrawal of British, French
and American forces from Berlin.
According to well-placed officials, the article was based on an interview
with Mr Francois Scheer, the French ambassador in Bonn, by Mr Claus
Gennrich, the respected diplomatic correspondent of the German newspaper.
In it, he suggests that the Normandy and Berlin incidents were only minor
upsets, but should be seen against the background of a general mistrust of
German foreign policy in Paris.
'A more fundamental dialogue is needed to create greater clarity between
Bonn and Paris over the definition of foreign policy in a united Germany,
but it is not taking place,' the newspaper said, citing the French sources.
The Frankfurter Allgemeine said the French were calling for German clarity
on its attitude towards eastern Europe, and the move of the seat of
government from Bonn to Berlin. They were seeking a 'clear restatement' of
Germany's commitment to western Europe, particularly if Bonn wished to
reinforce its relations with Russia.
The French officials are said to be worried by German statements from Mr
Klaus Kinkel, the foreign minister, suggesting that enlargement will 'shift
the balance' of the Community.
David Buchan adds from Paris: Mr Jean-Marie Girault, the mayor of Caen in
Normandy, yesterday weighed into the delicate diplomatic dilemma over
possible German presence at this summer's commemoration of the D-Day
landings by saying he hoped Mr Kohl would attend 'a peace ceremony' in his
city.
The Caen mayor, who is also a French senator, said he would invite the
German chancellor to a peace ceremony near the Caen war memorial on June 6.
'It is not easy to imagine Helmut Kohl on Omaha Beach where 3,000 American
soldiers died,' he said, 'but the ceremony on the evening of June 6 will try
to transcend military events and be an event for peace and reconciliation
among peoples,' Mr Girault said.
The French government has so far held back from inviting Mr Kohl to any part
of the 50th anniversary of the D-Day landings,but an opinion poll this week
showed that 57 per cent of French believed that Germany should be presented
at the Normandy celebrations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
