<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 94 / Heron faces threat from 'significant' danger of default
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The threat of receivership is again hanging over Heron International, the
property and trading group run by Mr Gerald Ronson, only six months after it
completed a Pounds 1.4bn refinancing.
Heron yesterday warned bondholders that it was 'currently exposed to a
number of significant uncertainties' and there was 'a significant potential
for cross defaults' on its debt. It also warned that interest due to
bondholders might be delayed further.
Some creditors doubted last summer whether Heron's business plan was
achievable because it relied on a recovery in the European property market.
Although there has since been an upturn in the UK, Heron said yesterday a
collapse in the Spanish property market had raised the risk of its
defaulting.
The group said a review of all its properties was being undertaken, and
initially showed that Heron would not now be able to repay its senior debt
by its due date of March 1997. This debt would have to be renegotiated.
Spanish difficulties also contributed to a net loss of Pounds 63.4m in the
six months to September 30, by when the group's negative net worth had
worsened to Pounds 157.8m from an adjusted figure of Pounds 109m six months
earlier.
Heron's interim results, prepared on the assumption that it was able to
continue trading, included a provision of Pounds 13.3m for a further fall in
property values and a Pounds 30.5m foreign exchange loss.
The group has called meetings of its bondholders to seek approval of a
deferral of interest, due on March 31, to June 30 on top of delays in debt
repayments and fees. In total, Heron is seeking to defer payments of Pounds
52.1m.
But Heron said recent events possibly meant a further deferral of interest
beyond June 30.
It expects to receive Pounds 75m from disposals by the end of June  - Pounds
31m from the sale of Heron Homes and Pounds 44m from the sale of the Heron
Suzuki motor distributor to Suzuki Motor Corporation. Under Heron's complex
banking arrangements, it cannot use this cash to meet head office
obligations.
Mr Ronson, formerly also Heron's chairman and owner, had led an investor
group which planned to buy Heron Suzuki. Heron said yesterday Mr Ronson had
no financial interest in the transaction. He would remain non-executive
chairman of Heron Suzuki but receive no salary.
</TEXT>
